    <!-- SECTION 1 -->
    <h2>Why Breakfast Protein Matters More After 40</h2>

    <p>I'm 64 and I've watched the same pattern repeat itself more times than I can count: a guy committed to hitting 120–140g of protein per day, eating well at lunch and dinner — and consistently falling short. The culprit is almost always breakfast.</p>

    <p>The typical American breakfast — cereal, toast, a couple of eggs, maybe some orange juice — comes in around 10–15g of protein. You're already in a hole before you've left the house. Catch-up protein later in the day is harder than you think, especially for men over 40.</p>

    <p>Here's the biology worth understanding: after 40, your muscles experience <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/">anabolic resistance</a> — they require a larger protein dose per meal to trigger the same muscle-building response younger men get from less. Research points to 30g as the floor per meal, with some evidence suggesting 40–50g is more effective for older adults. That means a two-egg breakfast isn't a protein meal. It's a protein snack.</p>

    <p>The good news: hitting 50g at breakfast with real food is simpler than most men expect once you know which foods to combine.</p>

