    <h2>The One Thing That Kills a High-Protein Breakfast</h2>

    <p>It's not effort. It's not time. It's not even knowing what to eat.</p>

    <p>It's not tracking it.</p>

    <p>The number one thing I hear from men who say they "eat pretty well at breakfast" is that when they actually log what they ate, they come in at 22–28g — not 50g. Greek yogurt with some granola and a couple of eggs feels like a lot of protein. It isn't. Feeling like you ate enough protein and knowing you hit your number are two completely different things.</p>

    <p>This is exactly what <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/best-protein-tracking-app/">a protein tracking app</a> is for — not the complicated ones that ask you to log every micronutrient, but a simple daily number you can see at a glance. Once you track breakfast for a week, you know your combos cold. The tracking becomes automatic.</p>

    <h2>What About Protein Shakes?</h2>

    <p>Shakes aren't off the table — this post just proves you don't need them. If you already make a shake and you like it, there's no reason to stop. But a lot of men default to shakes because they don't think whole-food alternatives are fast enough or filling enough. The combos above prove otherwise.</p>

    <p>There's also a satiety argument for whole food at breakfast. Eggs, cottage cheese, and Greek yogurt contain more volume, fiber, and fat alongside the protein than a shake does. For most men, that translates to staying fuller through the late morning without hitting a wall at 10am.</p>

