      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Can I really get 50g of protein at breakfast without a protein shake?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes. Whole eggs, Greek yogurt, and cottage cheese are all dense protein sources. One cup of cottage cheese alone is 25g. Combine it with three eggs and a few egg whites and you're at 50g before you've added anything else. No blender required.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Why should men over 40 aim for 50g of protein at breakfast?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Men over 40 experience anabolic resistance — their muscles need a larger protein dose per meal to trigger muscle protein synthesis. Research suggests 30g is the floor, with some evidence pointing to 40–50g being more effective for older adults. Hitting 50g at breakfast also front-loads your daily target, making the rest of the day significantly easier to hit.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What are the best high-protein breakfast foods for men over 40?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The highest-return options are cottage cheese (25g per cup), Greek yogurt (17–20g per cup), eggs combined with egg whites (18–32g depending on ratio), smoked salmon (16g per 3oz), and Canadian bacon (15g per 3oz). These are all whole foods with minimal prep and predictable protein counts.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Is 50g of protein at breakfast too much?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">No — especially for men over 40. Research suggests older adults can effectively use up to 40–50g of protein per meal for muscle protein synthesis, more than was previously assumed. Hitting 50g at breakfast is well within a healthy, productive range for men in this age group.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is the 30-gram protein rule for breakfast?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The 30-gram rule refers to the minimum per-meal protein threshold needed to meaningfully trigger muscle protein synthesis — particularly important for men over 40 due to anabolic resistance. Aiming for 40–50g at breakfast gives you a buffer above that floor and makes daily totals easier to hit.</div>
